        <section xml:id="SecondOrderHomogeneous">
        <title>Solution Technique 5: Linear Homogeneous Second-Order ODEs</title>
        <p>
            This note tells us how to solve constant-coefficient linear second-order homogeneous ODEs.    
        </p>
        <p xml:id="equation1">
            Suppose we wish to solve
            <me>
                ax'' + bx' + cx = 0.
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            We know how to rewrite this equation as a system of two first-order equations (called the <term>companion system</term> to the second-order equation) by making the substitution <m>x_1 = x</m> and <m>x_2 = x'</m>:
            <me>
                \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          x_1'(t) \\
          x_2'(t)
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      = 
       \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{rr}
          0 &amp; 1 \\
          -\frac{c}{a} &amp; -\frac{b}{a}
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          x_1(t) \\
          x_2(t)
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack.
            </me>
        We solve this system using the eigenvalue method. To do so, we solve
        <me>
         \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{rr}
          0 &amp; 1 \\
          -\frac{c}{a} &amp; -\frac{b}{a}
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          u \\
          v
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack 
      = 
      \lambda\left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          u \\
          v
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack.   
        </me>
         Observe that the first entry of the matrix product implies <m>v = \lambda u</m>, hence <m>\vec{\mathbf{v}} = \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          1 \\
          \lambda
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack</m>
will be an eigenvector for any eigenvalue of this matrix. Now plugging <m>u = 1</m> and <m>\lambda = v</m> in the second equation, we get  
<me>
-\frac{c}{a} - \frac{b}{a}\lambda = \lambda^2.
</me>
This is equivalent to 
<me>
a\lambda^2 + b\lambda +c = 0,
</me>
which we may solve using the quadratic formula. This yields the following three possibilities:
    </p>
<subsection xml:id="overdamped">
    <title>Case I: <m>b^2-4ac &gt; 0</m></title>
<p>
If <m>b^2 - 4ac &gt; 0</m>, there are two distinct real eigenvalues <m>\lambda_1</m>, <m>\lambda_2</m> with corresponding eigenvectors <m>\vec{\bf x}_1</m> and <m>\vec{\bf x}_2</m>.  Since the solution we are looking for is <m>x_1 = x</m> (and <m>x_2</m> is simply <m>x_1'</m>), we write the general solution as 
<me>    
     \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          x_1(t) \\
          x_2(t)
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      = 
      c_1 e^{\lambda_1 t}       \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          1 \\
          \lambda_1
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      +
      c_2 e^{\lambda_2 t}       \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          1 \\
          \lambda_2
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
</me>
Since <m>x(t)</m> is the function we want, the general solution of  <xref ref="equation1">the original equation</xref> is

  
<me>
     x(t) = c_1e^{\lambda_1 t} + c_2e^{\lambda_2 t}. 
</me>


(The system solution is still useful for solving initial value problems.)    



</p>


    
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="underdamped">
    <title>Case II: <m>b^2-4ac &lt; 0</m></title>
<p>
    If <m>b^2 - 4ac &lt; 0</m>, there are two distinct complex eigenvalues.  Remember that we can build the general solution out of only one eigenvalue, say <m>\lambda_1 = \alpha+\beta i</m>, and its corresponding eigenvector.  Since we only care about the first component <m>x_1 = x</m>, we can write 
<me>
e^{(\alpha+\beta i)t}       \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{c}
          1 \\
         \alpha + \beta i
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack   
      =
      e^{\alpha t} \left(
            \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{c}
          \cos(\beta t) \\
          \alpha\cos(\beta t) -\beta\sin(\beta t)
         \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
          + i
         \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{c}
          \sin(\beta t) \\
          \beta\cos(\beta t) + \alpha\sin(\beta t)
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
            \right).
</me>
The real-valued solution to the system is given by
<me>
   \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          x_1(t) \\
          x_2(t)
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      =
      c_1 e^{\alpha t}
            \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{c}
          \cos(\beta t) \\
          \alpha\cos(\beta t) -\beta\sin(\beta t)
         \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      +
      c_1 e^{\alpha t}       
      \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{c}
          \sin(\beta t) \\
          \beta\cos(\beta t) + \alpha\sin(\beta t)
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack.
</me>
Thus, we obtain the general solution of  <xref ref="equation1">the original equation</xref>:
<me> x(t) = e^{\alpha t} [ c_1\cos(\beta t) + c_2\sin(\beta t)].</me>
</p>


    
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="crit-damped">
  <title>Case III: <m>b^2-4ac = 0</m></title>
<p>
If <m>b^2 - 4ac = 0</m>, we have one real (repeated) eigenvalue <m>\lambda = -\frac{b}{2a}</m>.  We can still build a fundamental set of solutions and get the general solution of the form:
<me>
\left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          x_1(t) \\
          x_2(t)
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      = 
      c_1 e^{-\frac{b}{2a} t}       \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          1 \\
          -\frac{b}{2a}
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      +
      c_2 \left( t e^{-\frac{b}{2a} t}       \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          1 \\
          -\frac{b}{2a}
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
        +
      e^{-\frac{b}{2a} t}       \left\lbrack
        \begin{array}{r}
          0 \\
          1
        \end{array}
      \right\rbrack
      \right)  
</me>
Thus, the general solution of  <xref ref="equation1">the original equation</xref> is
<me>
   x(t) = c_1e^{-\frac{b}{2a} t} + c_2t e^{-\frac{b}{2a} t}.
</me>

</p>
  
</subsection>
   


